alternatives.transcript: two year old male presents to the emergency department department with complaints of dyspnea fatigue palpitations and the feeling of passing out after going on a walk with friends he claims it started two weeks ago while on a walk and since then he stopped walking he stated that the dyspnea felt better while laying down he also stated that it makes him feel weak and tired in his review of systems generally he just felt fatigued but had no weight loss or gain or fever he had no skin no neurological no musculoskeletal problems no headaches no hearing loss no vision change no trouble swallowing or no stiff neck he claims to have palpitations but no chest pain he has dyspnea that is better laying down so no orthopnea and he claims to have wheezing but no cough he has a history of hypertension and he had a heart catheter placed and abnormal ekg one year ago his father died of a myocardial infarction at fifty nine and his mom died suddenly of an unknown cause at forty patient is currently on ten milligrams of lisinopril and he has no known drug allergies patient has a well balanced diet exercises daily but stopped two weeks ago when symptoms presented he has no history of alcohol tobacco or illicit drugs he drinks one to two cups of coffee daily he's been married for thirty years and works as an elementary school teacher his his vital signs were ninety six percent oxygen a hundred and ten heart rate temperature of ninety eight point six degrees fahrenheit and a blood pressure of a hundred and thirty knot a hundred and thirty over ninety millimeters of mercury on his physical exam i found a positive systolic murmur his lungs were cleared a auscultation bilaterally no jugular venous distension no carotid bruise no tenderness to chest palpation no lower extremity edema his pulses were full and equal bilaterally and his calves were nontender diagnosed him with familial hypertrophic cardiomyopathy secondary to hypertension and i ordered him to be admitted to telemetry under serious condition and his vitals will be checked every two hours he can do activity as tolerated the nursing instructions are to check weight daily and then strict intake and output dvt prophylaxis nasal cannula and then maintain o two greater than ninety six percent he can have a regular diet and like i said he has no allergies no labs were needed to be ordered no imaging was needed to be ordered and then for iv fluids keep vein open and then i added one hundred milligrams of diisopyramide by mouth four times a day and then we're gonna discontinue the lisinopril we're gonna consult interventional cardiology for an automatic implantable cardioverter defibrillator and then we're gonna consult a cardiothoracic surgeon for septal myectomy and alcohol injection thank you
